    "summary": "The Battle of Balaclava, fought on 25 October 1854 during the [[event:2547|Crimean War]], is remembered less for its tactical outcome — which was inconclusive — than for the Charge of the Light Brigade, one of the most celebrated and catastrophic cavalry actions in military history, and for the 'Thin Red Line,' the disciplined stand of the 93rd Highland Regiment that became an enduring image of British military steadfastness.\n\nThe battle began as a Russian sortie against the allied supply base at Balaclava harbor. The British Heavy Brigade successfully charged and repulsed a much larger Russian cavalry force in one of the day's first actions. The 'Thin Red Line' episode followed shortly after: when Russian cavalry threatened the base itself, the 93rd Highlanders stood their ground in a double line rather than the usual square formation, repelling the Russian horsemen by disciplined volley fire. The action entered British folklore immediately, the phrase coined by correspondent William Howard Russell.\n\nThe Charge of the Light Brigade followed from a catastrophic miscommunication between Lord Raglan, commanding from the heights, and Lord Lucan commanding the cavalry below. Raglan intended the Light Brigade to pursue retreating Russian artillery; the written order was misunderstood, and Lord Cardigan led the brigade directly up a valley commanded on three sides by Russian guns. Of approximately 670 horsemen who rode, around 110 were killed and 160 wounded. Alfred Lord Tennyson's poem 'The Charge of the Light Brigade,' written within weeks of the battle, immortalized the action and the men who died in it, and the battle became a touchstone for the tension between courageous obedience and the consequences of military incompetence.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Balaclava",
